Yes, you can use CSS to change the color of radio buttons. Here's an example:

HTML:
```
<input type="radio" name="color" id="red" value="red">
<label for="red">Red</label>

<input type="radio" name="color" id="blue" value="blue">
<label for="blue">Blue</label>
```

CSS:
```
input[type="radio"] {
  display: none;
}

label {
  display: inline-block;
  padding: 10px;
  background-color: #ccc;
  color: #fff;
  cursor: pointer;
}

input[type="radio"]:checked + label {
  background-color: blue;
}
```

In this example, we hide the actual radio buttons using `display: none;`. Then, we style the associated labels to look like buttons using `padding`, `background-color`, and `color`. When a radio button is checked, we use the `+` selector in CSS to style the label accordingly. In this case, the background color is changed to blue.

You can customize the CSS properties to achieve the desired button color and style.

Sure! Here's an example of a commonly used radio button style with modern and sleek styling:

HTML:
```
<div class="radio-btn">
  <input type="radio" name="color" id="red" value="red">
  <label for="red">Red</label>
</div>

<div class="radio-btn">
  <input type="radio" name="color" id="blue" value="blue">
  <label for="blue">Blue</label>
</div>
```

CSS:
```
.radio-btn {
  display: inline-block;
  margin-right: 10px;
}

.radio-btn input[type="radio"] {
  position: absolute;
  opacity: 0;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.radio-btn label {
  display: inline-block;
  padding: 10px 20px;
  margin-bottom: 10px;
  font-size: 14px;
  font-weight: bold;
  text-align: center;
  color: #fff;
  background-color: #ccc;
  border-radius: 5px;
  transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
  cursor: pointer;
}

.radio-btn input[type="radio"]:checked + label {
  background-color: #007bff;
}
```

In this example, we wrap the radio buttons in a `div` element with the class name `radio-btn` to create a container. The CSS is then applied to style the radio buttons and labels within that container.

The radio buttons are hidden by setting `opacity: 0;`. The labels are styled with padding, font size, font weight, and border radius to create a button-like appearance. The `transition` property is used to add a smooth color change effect on hover.

When a radio button is checked, the background color of its corresponding label changes to a different color (`#007bff` in this example) using the `:checked` pseudo-class.

Feel free to customize the CSS properties to match your desired stylings.

In JavaScript, the `+=` operator is not typically used directly in combination with an `await` expression. This is because the `await` keyword is used to pause the execution of an asynchronous function until a promise is resolved, and the `+=` operator is used for concatenation or addition operations.

However, if you want to append or accumulate values within an `await` expression, you can use a separate variable and then use the `+=` operator outside the `await` expression. Here's an example:

```javascript
async function fetchData() {
  let accumulatedData = '';

  const data1 = await promiseFunction1();
  accumulatedData += data1;

  const data2 = await promiseFunction2();
  accumulatedData += data2;

  console.log(accumulatedData);
}

fetchData();

async function promiseFunction1() {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve('Hello, ');
    }, 1000);
  });
}

async function promiseFunction2() {
  return new Promise(resolve => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      resolve('world!');
    }, 1000);
  });
}
```

In this example, `fetchData()` is an asynchronous function that uses `await` to pause the execution until each promise (`promiseFunction1()` and `promiseFunction2()`) is resolved. The `accumulatedData` variable is initialized outside the `await` expressions, and the `+=` operator is used to append the resolved values of the promises.

Note that the `fetchData()` function is marked as `async` to allow the usage of `await`. Also, keep in mind that the promises `promiseFunction1()` and `promiseFunction2()` are just examples and can be replaced with your actual asynchronous operations.

