Certainly! Here's an example of how you can add an HTML element dynamically using JavaScript:

HTML:
```html
<div id="container">
  <!-- Existing content -->
</div>
```

JavaScript:
```javascript
// Create a new HTML element
var newElement = document.createElement("p");
newElement.textContent = "This is a dynamically added element.";

// Get the container where you want to append the element
var container = document.getElementById("container");

// Append the new element to the container
container.appendChild(newElement);
```

In this example, we create a new `p` element using `document.createElement()`. We set the text content of the element using the `textContent` property. Then, we retrieve the container element using `document.getElementById()`. Finally, we use `appendChild()` to add the new element as a child of the container element.

After running this code, the new paragraph element (`<p>This is a dynamically added element.</p>`) will be appended to the container element in the HTML.

Please note that you can customize the created element (e.g., modify its attributes, add CSS classes, etc.) before appending it to the container.

To use icons in Sigma.js, you can leverage the Label Renderers provided by the library. Here's a basic example:

1. Include the necessary libraries in your HTML:
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Sigma.js Icon Example</title>
  <script src="https://unpkg.com/sigma/"></script>
  <script src="https://unpkg.com/sigma/renderers/sigma.renderers.html.labels.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="container"></div>
</body>
</html>
```

2. Initialize Sigma.js and define a custom label renderer:
```javascript
const s = new sigma({
  renderer: {
    container: document.getElementById('container'),
    type: 'canvas',
  },
});

s.renderers.def = new sigma.renderers.canvas(s);

s.graph.addNode({
  id: 'node1',
  label: 'Node 1',
  x: 0,
  y: 0,
});

s.refresh();

sigma.canvas.labels.def = (function (node, context, settings) {
  const { label, x, y } = node;

  // Render an icon using an image URL
  const image = new Image();
  image.src = 'path/to/icon.png';
  const size = 24; // Icon size

  context.drawImage(image, x - size / 2, y - size / 2, size, size);

  // Render the label text
  context.fillText(label, x, y + size / 2);
})(s.graph.getNode('node1'), s.renderers[0].context, s.settings);
```

In this example, we create a Sigma.js instance and define a custom label renderer using `sigma.canvas.labels.def`. Inside the custom renderer, we first render an icon using `context.drawImage` by providing the image URL and specifying the icon's size and position. Then, we render the label text using `context.fillText` underneath the icon.

Make sure to replace `'path/to/icon.png'` with the correct path to your desired icon image file. Adjust the `size` and positioning according to your needs.

This is a basic example, and you can further customize the label renderer to fit your specific requirements, such as using different icons or rendering based on node attributes.

Note: You may need to adjust the Sigma.js library version and paths based on your project setup.
